Alice\nOpen. High.\nAngust\nonly 6 points\n\nHS0\n12%\nrma\nQctober avsarsisnsatisrsasal Od\nEl i aaaanl\n5\nEESRY\n{4444\nNew York, June 10.\u2014Bradstreet's re\nview of the state of trade to-morrow will\nsays:\n\u201cUnseasonably cool weather still ar\nrests retail trade and retards crop prog\nress in the northern haif of the country,\nand trade Is quiet in the Southern dis\ntricts, though cotton and fruit crops there\nare making progress. Jobbing trade re\nports reflect quiet in consumptive demand\nin a moderate volume of reorders, which\nare classified as fairly frequent, but small\nin the aggregate. Fell trade as a whole\nstill hesitates, pending clearer views of\ncrop and price outcome. Industrial re\nports point to considerable curtailment\nof output proceeding from uncertainty as\nto the latter. Hot, forcing weather Is\nstill looked forward to hopefully as tend\ning to stimulate crop development and\nconsumptive demand. Cecllections range\nfrom slow to fair. Export trade still\nshows the effect bf high prices upon for\neign demand for farm products.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\u201cSome of the events of the week are,\nhowever, encouraging. The temporary\nsettlement of the railway rate trouble\nand the postponement of advances in this\nitem of cost of business operation have\ngiven a brighter tinge to feeling in some\nbasic industries. Much contemplated\nrailway improvement work, reported\nhalted last week, will be continued, with\nconsequent stimulation to demand, and\nthis has made for a better feeling In the\nsecurities market, with accompanying\nrallies in quotations, though there is still\n\n\n\n\n\nsome nervousness as to the ultimate out.\ncome.\u201d\n\nDAILY COURT RECORD.\nContinued from Page Ten,\n2; Gouge B. Hepetti ot uz. ot al 0 Bia\nWeller,\nTre ee 0, ian, between D and E\u2014Square\n3008, lot 183; Amanda Vinson et vir to Jeremiah\nH.\n\n\nto John H. Ringe,\nbury et ux. to Hermann Fischer, $10.\nloi 13; Damel\n$10.\nof lot 8;\nPayne to Anna C. Payne, $10.\